SHARING DATA BETWEEN APP AND NODES:

Based on the architectural plan, managing state in a hybrid Sprotty/React environment requires a clear separation of concerns. You are effectively running two state management systems side-by-side: Sprotty's SModel (for topology, layout, and bounds) and React's State/Context (for business data and UI interactivity).
Here is the strategy to share state effectively between them.

1. Sharing Application State with Nodes (App → Nodes)
Since the proposed architecture uses React Portals rendered by a top-level <SprottyDiagram> component, you gain a massive advantage: Context preservation.
Unlike creating separate React roots for every node (which would sever the Context chain), Portals exist within the same React component tree as their parent.
Strategy: Wrap your <SprottyDiagram> in your application's providers (Redux, Theme, UserContext).
Result: Any React component rendered inside a diagram node (e.g., <TaskNode />) can standard hooks like useSelector, useContext, or useQuery immediately.
Implementation:
TypeScript

// App.tsx
<ReduxProvider store={store}>
   <ThemeProvider theme={myTheme}>
      {/*All nodes inside here can access Redux and Theme automatically*/}
      <SprottyDiagram modelSource={source} />
   </ThemeProvider>
</ReduxProvider>

1. Sharing Sprotty State with Nodes (Nodes → Sprotty)
Nodes frequently need to tell the diagram engine to do something (e.g., "delete me", "select me", "resize me").
Strategy: Expose the Sprotty IActionDispatcher via a custom React Context.
Implementation: The sprotty-react middleware should initialize a SprottyDispatchContext. When the diagram starts, it pulls the dispatcher from the Inversify container and provides it to the React tree.
TypeScript

// Inside your custom Node component
import { useSprottyDispatch } from 'sprotty-react';

const MyNode = ({ model }) => {
   const dispatch = useSprottyDispatch();

   const handleRemove = () => {
      // Dispatch a standard Sprotty action to the underlying system
      dispatch({ kind: 'elementDeleted', elementIds: [model.id] });
   };

   return <button onClick={handleRemove}>Delete Node</button>;
};

1. Synchronizing Node-to-Node State
There are two types of state to consider here: Graph State and Business State.
A. Graph State (Topology, Connections)
Mechanism: Single Source of Truth (SModel).
Flow: Node A dispatches an action 1 -> Sprotty Command Stack updates SModel -> Sprotty triggers an update -> ReactPortalService pushes new props to Node B.
Example: If Node A is "collapsed", Node B (its child) should disappear. Node A dispatches CollapseAction. Sprotty updates the model, hiding children. The Portal Registry removes Node B's portal.
B. Business State (Form Data, API Status)
Mechanism: Shared React State / External Store.
Flow: Use your external state manager (Redux/Zustand).
Example: If Node A and Node B both display the same "Server Status", they should both subscribe to the same Redux slice. When the slice updates, React re-renders both nodes without waking up the Sprotty layout engine.
2. Critical Implementation Detail: Event Trapping
A major "gotcha" in this integration is Event Bubbling. React Portals bubble events to their React parent, but foreignObject elements bubble events to their DOM parent (the SVG container).
If a user clicks a "Save" button inside a Node, that click bubbles up to the SVG. Sprotty's MouseTool listens on the SVG background for selection clicks.
The Conflict: Clicking "Save" might accidentally select/deselect the node or trigger a drag operation.
The Fix: You must stop propagation at the portal root.
TypeScript

// Inside the React Portal Wrapper (provided by middleware)
<div
   onMouseDown={(e) => e.stopPropagation()}
   onClick={(e) => e.stopPropagation()}
>
   {userComponent}
</div>

